The democracy summit ended, and Biden said the fire of freedom will never be extinguished.
The online "Summit for Democracy," convened by US President Joe Biden and attended by governments, civil society and private sector leaders from 110 countries around the world, ended on Friday (December 10).
In his closing remarks, Biden said that the fire of freedom burns in the hearts of everyone in the world, and that authoritarian regimes can never extinguish it.
He also said that he plans to hold the second global "democracy summit" next year.
Taiwanese government representative and political councillor Tang Feng and Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Law Guanchong, who is currently in exile in the UK, also spoke at the summit on the second day.
"We know how difficult the work ahead of us is," Biden said.
But we also know that we can meet challenges, because as I said before, as this summit has shown, the democratic world is everywhere.
An authoritarian regime can never extinguish the small fire of freedom, which burns in the hearts of people around the world and around the world."
Biden also said that defending democracy requires the joint efforts of the whole society.
"As leaders of government, we have a responsibility to listen to our citizens, strengthen the guardrails of democracy, promote reforms, achieve transparent and accountable governance, and be more resistant to authoritarian buffers and shocks, as well as those who want to pursue power naked before the public good," he said.
The themes of the second day of the "Democracy Summit" were defending human rights, consolidating democracy and confronting authoritarianism, and countering digital authoritarianism and affirming democratic values.
This day coincides with "International Human Rights Day,".
In his opening speech on the same day, UN Secretary General Ant√≥nio Guterres also said that the cause of democracy faces challenges around the world, especially those brought about by emerging digital technologies.
"Now is the time to reaffirm common values and positions and democratic resilience," he said.
This requires deepening social dialogue, addressing inequality, fighting corruption, renewing the social contract, investing in quality education, and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
This also requires a firm condemnation of all forms of populism, nativism, and extremism, including the use of all the tools provided by the technological revolution."
Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Law Koon-chung addressed the summit through a pre-recorded video, reminding participants to continue to pay attention to the human rights situation of Hong Kong and ethnic minorities in China, including Uighurs and Tibetans.
"For a long time, the world has accepted China's rise, but has not established a mechanism to hold it accountable," he said.
This is why politicians and civil society leaders must work together.
We must use everything we have (resources) to ensure that the revival of democracy is our first priority.
Law also called on the free world to unite against the threat of the CCP.
He said: "Maybe some of you are afraid to annoy General Secretary Xi Jinping, maybe some of you don't want to lose the Chinese market, maybe some of you don't recognize the threat to our democratic values."
And that's why we failed.
This is why we have to change., "
During the roundtable discussion on "Combating Digital Dictatorship and Affirming Democratic Values," Tang Feng, a member of the Taiwan Executive Yuan, released the "National Statement" via video, stressing that Taiwan is at the forefront of the fight against authoritarianism and authoritarianism.
He also shared his experience on how to fight the COVID-19 pandemic through information transparency and building mutual trust.
"As Taiwan's democracy is in the ascendant, we have always been firmly at the forefront of the global fight against authoritarianism, and have played a leading role in promoting global freedom, democracy and human rights," he said.
During the pandemic, authoritarian governments everywhere rationalized human rights violations in the name of public health and collective interests, and global democracy showed signs of regression.
However, in Taiwan, we can control the epidemic without sealing the city, and we can defeat false information without taking it off the shelves."
At the same time as the second day of the "Democracy Summit" was scheduled, the US Treasury Department announced that it would impose sanctions on 15 individuals and 10 entities from several countries, including China and North Korea, who were found to have committed serious human rights violations, and impose investment restrictions on a Chinese company that was found to have used surveillance technology to assist in human rights violations.
