Beijing astronomy enthusiast Anjiu photographed the Geminid meteor shower in Qinghai on December 13, 2018.
The parent body of most meteor showers is a periodic comet, but the parent body of the Geminid meteor shower is the asteroid 3200 Phaeton, an Apollo-type asteroid.
The Geminid meteor shower is also the second known meteor shower that is not "bred" by a comet.
Xiu Lipeng, director of the Tianjin Astronomical Society and an expert in astronomical science popularization, said that just like the New Year blockbuster, the Geminid meteor shower usually appears at the end of the year, and the "release schedule" can last from December 4 to 17.
The meteor shower is known for its large and stable flow, and is known as the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere, together with the Quadrant meteor shower and the Perseid meteor shower.
A notable feature of the Geminid meteor shower is that the meteors are slow, colorful, and there are many firestorms, which are suitable for both visual and astrophotography beginners.
Tianjin astronomy enthusiast Yang Jing photographed the Geminid meteor shower in Jizhou, Tianjin, on December 13, 2020.
